ife, Chu provides an informative and critical analysis of the impact of China's ascendency on the notion of "One Country, Two Cultures." Hong Kong can no longer function as a bridge between China and the world, writes Chu, and must now define itself from global, local, and national perspectives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aGlobalizationxSocial aspectsxChinaxHong Kong. 0aGlobalizationxSocial aspectszChinazHong Kong. 0aGroup identityxChinaxHong Kong. 0aGroup identityzChinazHong Kong. 0aNational characteristics, Chinese. 0aSocial changexChinaxHong Kong. 0aSocial changezChinazHong Kong. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aAsian Studies : Chinese Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Postcolonial Studies. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Film Studies. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 21st Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143844647940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438446479423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438446479/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles